#### Transportation

Transportation can include walking, driving, biking, or utilizing public transportation, such as subways and buses.<a href="#cite-37" title="Healthy People 2030, Office of Disease Prevention and Health Promotion, US Department of Health and Human Services, 2025, https://health.gov/healthypeople/objectives-and-data/browse-objectives/transportation>, accessed August 2025"><sup>37</sup></a> Access to transportation can affect all aspects of life including the ability to find or keep employment, the quantity and quality of food that can be accessed, and access to health care. Studies have shown that those with access to a car are less likely to miss appointments or delay care when compared to those relying on other forms of transportation.<a href="#cite-38" title="Elsevier Ltd., ScienceDirect, 2020, https://reader.elsevier.com/reader/sd/pii/S2590198220301494?token=CF722B942BA01129C596B52298FF8C7D1F1F4F21256458ED5630257A6DACF91D844AAC3FC8413BCC277B984F0630B7C3&originRegion=us-east-1&originCreation=20220804131701>, accessed August 2022"><sup>38</sup></a>

Westchester County had the highest percentage of households with no available vehicles at 14.2%. Putnam County had the lowest percentage of households with no available vehicles at 4.2%. All counties within the M-H Region were below the NYS rate with residents having more access to vehicles. [see Figure 33]

